The error message you received (Authentication failed: Please make sure your API Key is valid) is actually a massive clue. Standard AWS does not throw "API Key" errors (it throws UnrecognizedClientException). Furthermore, openai.gpt-oss-206-1:0 is not a native AWS Bedrock model.
This means your company is using an **Enterprise API Gateway or Proxy** (like LiteLLM or an internal firewall) that routes requests to OpenAI but disguises itself as Amazon Bedrock.
In your successful test script, boto3 was likely picking up standard AWS environment variables (like AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID) automatically. But because you named the variable AWS_BEARER_TOKEN_BEDROCK in our new .env file, LangChain and boto3 have absolutely no idea what that custom variable is, so they are sending a blank authentication payload to your company's gateway.
### The Fix: Injecting the Custom Token into llm.py
We need to explicitly tell boto3 to take your custom AWS_BEARER_TOKEN_BEDROCK and use it as the access key for the Bedrock client before handing it over to LangGraph.
